Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson criticised media coverage of comments he made yesterday, when he was reported as saying he wanted sterling to stay roughly where it was, specifying a rate of around 2.90 marks and 1.60 dlrs to the pound.
Holding up a newspaper report on his comments headed &ldquo;Exchange Rate Targets Set&rdquo; Lawson told journalists &ldquo;This story is a complete non-event.&rdquo;
He criticised the report, which said he was now targetting sterling against the dollar and mark.

U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz said it was up to the Agriculture Department to decide whether to offer subsidized wheat to the Soviet Union.
Shultz told the Newspaper Farm Editors of America that a wheat bonus offer to the Soviet Union &ldquo;is something that I basically leave to the Agriculture Department to figure out.&rdquo;
Last year, Shultz spoke out against President Reagan&rsquo;s decision to offer subsidized U.S. wheat to the Soviet Union &ndash; an offer Moscow spurned.

U.S. Interior Secretary Donald Hodel said he does not support an oil import fee as a means to stimulate domestic oil and gas production.
&ldquo;I am an advocate for incentives for exploration,&rdquo; Hodel said, but added, &ldquo;I do not favor an oil import fee.&rdquo;
&ldquo;It would inject the federal government so deeply back in to the process, we would never get the government out again, and I think that would be in the long term disinterest of the nation,&rdquo; Hodel said in an address to a group of local business executives.

Japan is faced with a mounting crisis over its huge trade surplus and recognizes that it must act more quickly to refocus its export driven economy, a senior Foreign Ministry official said.
&ldquo;The sense of crisis among the Japanese public as well as the government is increasing,&rdquo; Deputy Director General Hiroshi Hirabayashi told reporters. &ldquo;The need to accelerate the efforts (to restructure the economy) is well recognized.&rdquo;
Hirabayashi said that gradual progress had been made to refocus the Japanese economy, but admitted that it might not seem all that spectacular to foreign observers.

Britain is not considering any restriction of its present oil production, UK Energy Minister Alick Buchanan-Smith said.
Speaking to reporters at the Offshore Technology Conference, Buchanan-Smith said, &ldquo;No, we&rsquo;ve made that absolutely clear, we see no reason for changing (the production level).&rdquo;
Earlier today, Buchanan-Smith gave the go-ahead to Mobil Corp for two new North Sea developments &ndash; the Ness oil field and Beryl B subsea water injection project &ndash; totalling 96 mln dlrs (60 mln British pounds).

A leading regional banker said that it was axiomatic that despite market intervention, a country&rsquo;s currency will eventually fall to an exchange rate which balances its international trade and payments accounts.
John Medlin, president and chief executive officer for the First Wachovia Corp, said that &ldquo;substantial and rapid currency devaluations usually are followed in time by surging price inflation, spiralling interest rates and painful economic austerity.&rdquo;
Speaking to a banking trade group, he also said the peak of debt writeoff has not yet been reached.

A 0.4 pct rise in the March U.S. index of leading indicators points to continued moderate U.S. real economic growth, economists said.
&ldquo;The report is consistent with a modestly growing economy,&rdquo; said Steve Slifer of Lehman Government Securities Inc. &ldquo;The economy is not robust, but we&rsquo;re not heading into a recession either.&rdquo;
&ldquo;The report suggests more of the same: continued moderate growth,&rdquo; said Ward McCarthy of Merrill Lynch Government and Co Inc.

